<section>
  <title>7.1 Integration By Parts</title>
  
  <!-- The <m> and </m> will be like single dollar sign and <md> is for square brackets -->
  <slide>
    <title>Prime and Composite Numbers</title>
    <p>
      An integer <m>n\gt 1</m> is <term>prime</term> provided that the only positive integers dividing <m>n</m> are <m component="a">1</m><m component="b">\phantom{11}</m> and <m component="a">n</m><m component="b">\phantom{nn}</m>
    </p>
    <!-- \phantom leaves blank space as big as what you type in on the slides -->
    <p>
      An integer <m>n\gt 1</m> is <term>composite</term> provided that there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m component="a">1\lt m\lt n</m><m component="b">\phantom{1\lt m\lt n}</m> and <m component="a">m\mid n</m><m component="b">\phantom{m\mid n}</m>
    </p>
     <!-- component a is for the annotated version, i.e. what I project (and make it slides that are annotated), component b is what I'd give students  -->
  </slide>
  <slide>
    <title>Activity</title>
    <p>
      Is the following statement true?
    </p>
    <p>
      <q>If <m>n\gt 1</m> is an integer, then <m>n</m> is either prime or composite but not both.</q>
    </p>
    <p component="a">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            This is <em>true</em> because negating the definition of prime gives the definition of composite.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            We cannot have free variables in something we plan to prove. Any variable that is not explicitly quantified is assumed to have a universal quantifer applied.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </slide>
  <slide>
    <title>Mid-Slide Whitespace</title>
    <p>
      Suppose we want some space between these paragraphs to write in.
    </p>
    <p component="b">
      <nbsp/>
    </p>
    <p component="a">
      Here's what goes onto the annotated page.
    </p>
    <p>
      This comes next.
    </p>
  </slide>
<!-- To automatically convert from tex to pretext: highlight what I've pasted in, shift/command/p, pretext convert to pretext-->
<slide>
  <title>Example </title>
  <p>
  <m>
      \int x\cos(x) dx
  </m>
  </p>
  <p pause="yes">
    <m> u=x </m> 
  </p>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell><m>u=x</m></cell> 
         <cell><m>dv=\cos(x)dx</m></cell> 
        </row>
      </tabular>

      <tabular>
        <row top="none">
            <cell><m>du = 1 dx = dx</m></cell>
            <cell> <m>v= \int dv  =\int \cos(x)dx =\sin(x)</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
    

  <m>
      \int x\cos(x) dx = uv-\int v \; du 
  </m>
  <m>
      = x\sin(x) -\int \sin(x) dx = x\sin(x)  -(-\cos(x)) +C
  </m>
  <md>
      =x\sin(x)+\cos(x)+C
  </md>
  </slide>

  <!-- To gut and play with -->
  <slide>
  <title>Example Testing </title>
  <p>
  <m>
      \int x\cos(x) dx
  </m>
  </p>
    <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 25%">
        <p pause="yes"><m>u=x</m></p>
        <p pause="yes"><m>dv=\cos(x)dx</m></p>
        <p></p>
    </sidebyside>

    <sidebyside widths="33% 28% 3% 16%">
          <p pause="yes"><m>du = 1 dx = dx</m></p>
          <p pause="yes"><m>v= \int dv  =\int \cos(x)dx</m> </p>
          <p pause="yes"><m>=\sin(x)</m></p>
          <p></p>
    </sidebyside>
    <sidebyside widths="17% 35% 38%">
     <p pause="yes"><m>\int x\cos(x) dx </m></p>
      <p pause="yes"> <m> = uv-\int v \; du </m> </p>
      <p></p>
     </sidebyside>
    <sidebyside widths="14% 17% 15% 15% 10%">
      <p pause="yes"><m>= x\sin(x)</m></p>
      <p pause="yes"><m> -\int \sin(x) dx</m></p>
      <p pause="yes"><m> = x\sin(x)  -(-\cos(x))</m></p>
      <p pause="yes"><m> +C</m></p>
      <p></p>
     </sidebyside>
     <p pause="yes"><m>\hspace{.3in}</m> <m>=x\sin(x)+\cos(x)+C
  </m></p>
  </slide>
</section>